{"title_page": "Kalbe Jawad", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n\n'''''Maulana'' Syed Kalbe Jawad Naqvi''' (\u0645\u0648\u0644\u0627\u0646\u0627 \u0633\u064a\u062f \u0643\u0644\u0628 \u062c\u0648\u0627\u062f \u0646\u0642\u0648\u0649) is a [[Twelver]] [[Shia]] Muslim cleric and scholar from [[Lucknow]], [[India]].\n\n==Family background==\nHe comes from a family of scholars known as ''\"Khandan-e-Ijtehad\"''. He traces his lineage from [[Dildar Ali Naseerabadi|Syed Dildar Ali Naqvi ''Nasirabadi'']] (also known as [[Ghufran Ma'ab]]) His ancestors came to Jais from [[Sabzevar]]<ref name=\"Milli\">[http://www.milligazette.com/dailyupdate/2006/20060525_muslim_india_politics.htm The Milli Gazette Online, ''Who is Kalbe Jawwad'' By Rizvi Syed Haider Abbas, 24 May 2006]</ref> He is son of ''Maulana'' [[Kalbe Abid|Syed Kalbe Abid]]; ''Maulana'' [[Syed Kalbe Hussain]] was his grandfather and [[Dr. Kalbe Sadiq]] is his uncle.\n\n==Positions and activities==\n\nHe has held following positions:\n* ''Imam-e-Juma'' (leader of the Friday prayers) at the [[Asafi Imambara|Shahi Asafi Mosque]], [[Lucknow]].<ref name=\"Milli\"/><ref name=\"pasdaran-home\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pasdaranehussain.com/|title=Tanzeem-e-Pasdaran-e-Husain, home.|access-date=23 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110414115744/http://www.pasdaranehussain.com/|archive-date=14 April 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* Senior member of [[All India Muslim Personal Law Board]].<ref name=\"Milli\" />\n* Patron<ref>[http://www.shiayateemkhaana.com/committe.html shia yateem khaana, Lucknow, Committee] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120727013039/http://www.shiayateemkhaana.com/committe.html |date=27 July 2012 }}</ref> & chairman<ref>[http://www.shiayateemkhaana.com/ shia yateem khaana, Lucknow, Home] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090303180537/http://shiayateemkhaana.com/ |date=3 March 2009 }}</ref> of the committee of \"Shia Orphanage\" ''Gulistan-e-Abutalib a.s.'', Lucknow.\n* Member of the \"Joint Ulema Council\", founded after 19 February 2006.<ref name=\"Milli\" />\n* National President Rashtriya Shia Sufi Sangh\n* General Secretary Majlis e Ulama e Hind<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://majliseulamaehind.com/about_us.php|title=: : : : :  Majlis-E-Ulema-E-Hind  : : : : |website=majliseulamaehind.com|language=en|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2000 he founded an organization named ''Tanzeem-e-Pasdaran-e-Husain (a.s.)''.<ref name=\"pasdaran-home\"/>\n\n===Involvement in Azadari movement of Lucknow===\nHe led vigorous anti-government demonstrations at Lucknow in 1997 to lift two decades old ban on [[Azadari in Lucknow|Azadari processions in Lucknow]].<ref name=\"Milli\" /><ref name=\"pasdaran-aza\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pasdaranehussain.com/aza.html|title=Tanzeem-e-Pasdaran-e-Husain, Azadari Movement|access-date=23 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020142345/http://pasdaranehussain.com/aza.html|archive-date=20 October 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> He got arrested two times during the movement:<ref name=\"pasdaran-aza\"/>\n* He with Sunni clerics Maulana Qamar Minai and Imam Bukhari of Delhi were arrested on 3 June 1997 for organising a meeting and defying Section 144 I.P.C.\n* He was again arrested on 28 June 1997 at 4:00&nbsp;a.m. under National Security Act (NSA).\n\nThe [[Government of Uttar Pradesh|government]] later entered into a tripartite Shias-Sunnis-Administration agreement and nine main processions on the 1st, 7th, 8th, 9th, 10th Muharrum, Chehlum, 8th Rabiul Awwal and 21st Ramzan have been restored.<ref name=\"pasdaran-aza\"/>\n\n===Involvement in Waqf movement of Lucknow===\nThe \"Waqf Movement\" or ''Tehreek-e-Awqaf'' which is going on in Lucknow under his leadership has achieved significant success in Lucknow and Delhi (with Dargah e Shah Mardan case).<ref name=\"pasdaran-waqf\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pasdaranehussain.com/waqf.html|title=Tanzeem-e-Pasdaran-e-Husain, Waqf Movement|access-date=23 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020205335/http://pasdaranehussain.com/waqf.html|archive-date=20 October 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> He has been demanding CBI inquiry into the corruption taken place in UP Shia Central Waqf Board from a very long time. So far the governments have given assurance only.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bhaskar.com/news/UP-LUCK-maulana-kalbe-jawad-demand-cbi-probe-for-shia-waqf-board-5118985-PHO.html|title=\u0935\u0915\u094d\u200d\u092b \u092c\u094b\u0930\u094d\u0921 \u0915\u0940 \u0928\u0939\u0940\u0902 \u0939\u0941\u0908 CBI \u091c\u093e\u0902\u091a \u0924\u094b \u092a\u0942\u0930\u093e \u092e\u0941\u0939\u0930\u094d\u0930\u092e \u092c\u0921\u093c\u0947 \u0907\u092e\u093e\u092e\u092c\u093e\u0921\u093c\u0947 \u092e\u0947\u0902: \u092e\u094c\u0932\u093e\u0928\u093e \u0915\u0932\u094d\u200d\u092c\u0947 \u091c\u0935\u094d\u200d\u0935\u093e\u0926|date=20 September 2015|website=Dainik Bhaskar|language=hi|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref>\n\n* founder of noore hidayat foundation lucknow<ref>noorehidayatfoundation.org</ref> khumaini e hind\n\n===Involvement in demonstrations and rallies===\nHe is also famous for holding the biggest ever anti US/Israel/Denmark rally at Lucknow which was attended by over one million people.<ref name=\"pasdaran-news\">[http://www.pasdaranehussain.com/news.html Tanzeem-e-Pasdaran-e-Husain, News] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020190045/http://pasdaranehussain.com/news.html |date=20 October 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/Cleric-detained--supporters-go-on-rampage-in-Lucknow/711205 | title=Cleric detained, supporters go on rampage in Lucknow | newspaper=[[The Indian Express|Express news service]] | date=15 November 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-11-15/lucknow/28229849_1_shia-cleric-lucknow-road-maulana-kalbe-jawwad | title=Shia tussle spills on to Lucknow road | newspaper=[[Times of India|TNN]] | date=15 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/article886463.ece | title=Dispute over college sparks violence | newspaper=[[The Hindu]] | location=[[Lucknow]] | date=15 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Row-over-Shia-College/Article1-626215.aspx | title=Row over Shia College | first=Rohit | last=Singh | newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]] | location=[[Lucknow]] | date=14 November 2010 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101203202837/http://www.hindustantimes.com/Row-over-Shia-College/Article1-626215.aspx | archivedate=3 December 2010 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Execution of Nimr al-Nimr===\nIn an interview condemning the [[execution of Nimr al-Nimr]] in [[Saudi Arabia]] which was posted on the Internet on 3 January 2016 (as translated by [[MEMRI]]), Jawad accused [[Israel]] and the [[United States]] to be involved in the execution, stating that:  \"Israeli and American hands are involved in [the execution of Sheikh Al-Nimr in Saudi Arabia] and so are other Arab countries, which have unleashed cruelty on the minorities, and are supporting and backing terrorism. They are all involved in this. They don't want any voices to be raised against terrorism.\"<ref>{{YouTube|id=LMXi83fe0lolist=UUweyNwo4cZM5gsIpuG4Zlew|title=\"MAULANA S KALBE JAWAD CONDEMS KILING OF SHIA CLERIC SHEIKH NIMR\"}}</ref><ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Indian-Shias-outraged-at-the-execution-of-Saudi-cleric-Sheikh-Nimr-call-for-nationwide-protest/articleshow/50418846.cms Indian Shias outraged at the execution of Saudi cleric Sheikh Nimr, call for nationwide protest], [[The Times of India]], 2 January 2016.</ref>\n\n===Wahhabism and Jews===\nIn the same interview Jawad compared practitioners of [[Wahhabism]] in [[Saudi Arabia]] to [[Judaism|Jews]], stating that: \"This is the path of the Jews. According to their [[Talmud]], none but the Jews have the right to live. The Jewish mentality and the Wahhabi mentality are one and the same. That is why we say that there is no difference between the Saudis and the Jews. Their policies are the same, and they support one another. In fact, the Jews are their patrons.\"<ref>[http://www.memritv.org/clip_transcript/en/5309.htm Shiite Indian Cleric Kalbe Jawad: Jewish and Wahhabi Mentality Responsible for Terrorism], [[MEMRI]], Clip No. 5309 (transcript) (Video clip [http://www.memritv.org/clip/en/0/0/0/0/0/0/5309.htm available here]), 3 January 2016.</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|2899923}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110414115744/http://www.pasdaranehussain.com/ Pasdarane Husain - Website of an organisation run by Maulana Syed Kalbe Jawwad]\n* [http://www.milligazette.com/dailyupdate/2006/20060525_muslim_india_politics.htm An article entitled \"Who is Kalbe Jawwad\"]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jawad, Kalbe}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Muslim scholars of Islam]]\n[[Category:Scholars from Lucknow]]\n[[Category:Indian Shia Muslims]]\n[[Category:Shia Muslim scholars]]\n[[Category:Indian Islamic religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Indian Shia clerics]]\n[[Category:Ijtihadi family]]\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox religious biography|religion=[[Islam]]\n|honorific_prefix =\n|name             = Kalbe Jawad \n|image            = File:Syed Kalbe Jawad Naqvi 2010-11-30.jpg\n|caption          = \n|title            = Hujjatul Islam wal Muslimin Sayyedul Fuqaha wa Mujtahideen\n|birth_name       = \n| birth_date      =\n|birth_place      = \n|death_cause =\n|resting_place    =\n|other_names      = \n|nationality      = Indian \n|ethnicity        = \n|era              = \n|region           = [[Uttar Pradesh]]\n|occupation       = Imam e Jumma, Lucknow <br> Member of [[All India Muslim Personal Law Board]]\n|denomination     = \n|jurisprudence    = \n|movement         = \n|main_interests   = \n|notable_ideas    = \n|notable_works    =\n|alma_mater       = \n|Sufi_order       =\n|disciple_of      =\n|awards           =\n|influences       = \n|influenced       =\n|module           = \n|website          =\n}}\n'''''Maulana'' Syed Kalbe Jawad Naqvi''' (\u0645\u0648\u0644\u0627\u0646\u0627 \u0633\u064a\u062f \u0643\u0644\u0628 \u062c\u0648\u0627\u062f \u0646\u0642\u0648\u0649) is a [[Twelver]] [[Shia]] Muslim cleric and scholar from [[Lucknow]], [[India]].\n\n==Family background==\nHe comes from a family of scholars known as ''\"Khandan-e-Ijtehad\"''. He traces his lineage from [[Dildar Ali Naseerabadi|Syed Dildar Ali Naqvi ''Nasirabadi'']] (also known as [[Ghufran Ma'ab]]) His ancestors came to Jais from [[Sabzevar]]<ref name=\"Milli\">[http://www.milligazette.com/dailyupdate/2006/20060525_muslim_india_politics.htm The Milli Gazette Online, ''Who is Kalbe Jawwad'' By Rizvi Syed Haider Abbas, 24 May 2006]</ref> He is son of ''Maulana'' [[Kalbe Abid|Syed Kalbe Abid]]; ''Maulana'' [[Syed Kalbe Hussain]] was his grandfather and [[Dr. Kalbe Sadiq]] is his uncle.\n\n==Positions and activities==\n\nHe has held following positions:\n* ''Imam-e-Juma'' (leader of the Friday prayers) at the [[Asafi Imambara|Shahi Asafi Mosque]], [[Lucknow]].<ref name=\"Milli\"/><ref name=\"pasdaran-home\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pasdaranehussain.com/|title=Tanzeem-e-Pasdaran-e-Husain, home.|access-date=23 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110414115744/http://www.pasdaranehussain.com/|archive-date=14 April 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* Senior member of [[All India Muslim Personal Law Board]].<ref name=\"Milli\" />\n* Patron<ref>[http://www.shiayateemkhaana.com/committe.html shia yateem khaana, Lucknow, Committee] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120727013039/http://www.shiayateemkhaana.com/committe.html |date=27 July 2012 }}</ref> & chairman<ref>[http://www.shiayateemkhaana.com/ shia yateem khaana, Lucknow, Home] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090303180537/http://shiayateemkhaana.com/ |date=3 March 2009 }}</ref> of the committee of \"Shia Orphanage\" ''Gulistan-e-Abutalib a.s.'', Lucknow.\n* Member of the \"Joint Ulema Council\", founded after 19 February 2006.<ref name=\"Milli\" />\n* National President Rashtriya Shia Sufi Sangh\n* General Secretary Majlis e Ulama e Hind<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://majliseulamaehind.com/about_us.php|title=: : : : :  Majlis-E-Ulema-E-Hind  : : : : |website=majliseulamaehind.com|language=en|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2000 he founded an organization named ''Tanzeem-e-Pasdaran-e-Husain (a.s.)''.<ref name=\"pasdaran-home\"/>\n\n===Involvement in Azadari movement of Lucknow===\nHe led vigorous anti-government demonstrations at Lucknow in 1997 to lift two decades old ban on [[Azadari in Lucknow|Azadari processions in Lucknow]].<ref name=\"Milli\" /><ref name=\"pasdaran-aza\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pasdaranehussain.com/aza.html|title=Tanzeem-e-Pasdaran-e-Husain, Azadari Movement|access-date=23 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020142345/http://pasdaranehussain.com/aza.html|archive-date=20 October 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> He got arrested two times during the movement:<ref name=\"pasdaran-aza\"/>\n* He with Sunni clerics Maulana Qamar Minai and Imam Bukhari of Delhi were arrested on 3 June 1997 for organising a meeting and defying Section 144 I.P.C.\n* He was again arrested on 28 June 1997 at 4:00&nbsp;a.m. under National Security Act (NSA).\n\nThe [[Government of Uttar Pradesh|government]] later entered into a tripartite Shias-Sunnis-Administration agreement and nine main processions on the 1st, 7th, 8th, 9th, 10th Muharrum, Chehlum, 8th Rabiul Awwal and 21st Ramzan have been restored.<ref name=\"pasdaran-aza\"/>\n\n===Involvement in Waqf movement of Lucknow===\nThe \"Waqf Movement\" or ''Tehreek-e-Awqaf'' which is going on in Lucknow under his leadership has achieved significant success in Lucknow and Delhi (with Dargah e Shah Mardan case).<ref name=\"pasdaran-waqf\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pasdaranehussain.com/waqf.html|title=Tanzeem-e-Pasdaran-e-Husain, Waqf Movement|access-date=23 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020205335/http://pasdaranehussain.com/waqf.html|archive-date=20 October 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> He has been demanding CBI inquiry into the corruption taken place in UP Shia Central Waqf Board from a very long time. So far the governments have given assurance only.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bhaskar.com/news/UP-LUCK-maulana-kalbe-jawad-demand-cbi-probe-for-shia-waqf-board-5118985-PHO.html|title=\u0935\u0915\u094d\u200d\u092b \u092c\u094b\u0930\u094d\u0921 \u0915\u0940 \u0928\u0939\u0940\u0902 \u0939\u0941\u0908 CBI \u091c\u093e\u0902\u091a \u0924\u094b \u092a\u0942\u0930\u093e \u092e\u0941\u0939\u0930\u094d\u0930\u092e \u092c\u0921\u093c\u0947 \u0907\u092e\u093e\u092e\u092c\u093e\u0921\u093c\u0947 \u092e\u0947\u0902: \u092e\u094c\u0932\u093e\u0928\u093e \u0915\u0932\u094d\u200d\u092c\u0947 \u091c\u0935\u094d\u200d\u0935\u093e\u0926|date=20 September 2015|website=Dainik Bhaskar|language=hi|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref>\n\n* founder of noore hidayat foundation lucknow<ref>noorehidayatfoundation.org</ref> khumaini e hind\n\n===Involvement in demonstrations and rallies===\nHe is also famous for holding the biggest ever anti US/Israel/Denmark rally at Lucknow which was attended by over one million people.<ref name=\"pasdaran-news\">[http://www.pasdaranehussain.com/news.html Tanzeem-e-Pasdaran-e-Husain, News] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020190045/http://pasdaranehussain.com/news.html |date=20 October 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/Cleric-detained--supporters-go-on-rampage-in-Lucknow/711205 | title=Cleric detained, supporters go on rampage in Lucknow | newspaper=[[The Indian Express|Express news service]] | date=15 November 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-11-15/lucknow/28229849_1_shia-cleric-lucknow-road-maulana-kalbe-jawwad | title=Shia tussle spills on to Lucknow road | newspaper=[[Times of India|TNN]] | date=15 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/article886463.ece | title=Dispute over college sparks violence | newspaper=[[The Hindu]] | location=[[Lucknow]] | date=15 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Row-over-Shia-College/Article1-626215.aspx | title=Row over Shia College | first=Rohit | last=Singh | newspaper=[[Hindustan Times]] | location=[[Lucknow]] | date=14 November 2010 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101203202837/http://www.hindustantimes.com/Row-over-Shia-College/Article1-626215.aspx | archivedate=3 December 2010 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Execution of Nimr al-Nimr===\nIn an interview condemning the [[execution of Nimr al-Nimr]] in [[Saudi Arabia]] which was posted on the Internet on 3 January 2016 (as translated by [[MEMRI]]), Jawad accused [[Israel]] and the [[United States]] to be involved in the execution, stating that:  \"Israeli and American hands are involved in [the execution of Sheikh Al-Nimr in Saudi Arabia] and so are other Arab countries, which have unleashed cruelty on the minorities, and are supporting and backing terrorism. They are all involved in this. They don't want any voices to be raised against terrorism.\"<ref>{{YouTube|id=LMXi83fe0lolist=UUweyNwo4cZM5gsIpuG4Zlew|title=\"MAULANA S KALBE JAWAD CONDEMS KILING OF SHIA CLERIC SHEIKH NIMR\"}}</ref><ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Indian-Shias-outraged-at-the-execution-of-Saudi-cleric-Sheikh-Nimr-call-for-nationwide-protest/articleshow/50418846.cms Indian Shias outraged at the execution of Saudi cleric Sheikh Nimr, call for nationwide protest], [[The Times of India]], 2 January 2016.</ref>\n\n===Wahhabism and Jews===\nIn the same interview Jawad compared practitioners of [[Wahhabism]] in [[Saudi Arabia]] to [[Judaism|Jews]], stating that: \"This is the path of the Jews. According to their [[Talmud]], none but the Jews have the right to live. The Jewish mentality and the Wahhabi mentality are one and the same. That is why we say that there is no difference between the Saudis and the Jews. Their policies are the same, and they support one another. In fact, the Jews are their patrons.\"<ref>[http://www.memritv.org/clip_transcript/en/5309.htm Shiite Indian Cleric Kalbe Jawad: Jewish and Wahhabi Mentality Responsible for Terrorism], [[MEMRI]], Clip No. 5309 (transcript) (Video clip [http://www.memritv.org/clip/en/0/0/0/0/0/0/5309.htm available here]), 3 January 2016.</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|2899923}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110414115744/http://www.pasdaranehussain.com/ Pasdarane Husain - Website of an organisation run by Maulana Syed Kalbe Jawwad]\n* [http://www.milligazette.com/dailyupdate/2006/20060525_muslim_india_politics.htm An article entitled \"Who is Kalbe Jawwad\"]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jawad, Kalbe}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Muslim scholars of Islam]]\n[[Category:Scholars from Lucknow]]\n[[Category:Indian Shia Muslims]]\n[[Category:Shia Muslim scholars]]\n[[Category:Indian Islamic religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Indian Shia clerics]]\n[[Category:Ijtihadi family]]\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n", "name_user": "Miklos Mate", "label": "safe", "comment": "I added few essentials.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kalbe_Jawad"}
{"title_page": "Beam Breakers", "text_new": "{{reimprove|date = September 2017}}\n{{infobox video game\n|title = Beam Breakers\n|image = [[File:Beambreakers.jpg]]\n|caption = Cover art by Michel Bohbot\n|developer = Similis\n|publisher = [[JoWooD Productions]]\n|released = 2002\n|platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]] \n}}\n\n\n\n'''''Beam Breakers''''' is a [[racing video game|racing game]] released in 2002. It was published by [[JoWooD Productions]] and developed by Similis. The game takes place in the year 2173. It features flying cars in the city of New York.\n\n==Gameplay==\nThe highways of [[New York City]] are teeming with illegal rush-hour grave-racers. Bad racers end up scraped off the side of skyscrapers while good ones build reputations that some would literally kill for. This is no pedestrian street race scene. It's a contest of minds where confidence, control and a taste for razor's-edge maneuvers separate the original gangsters of the skies from the wannabes and has-been.\n\nBeam Breakers has five cities in 57-mission campaigns. The player has to dodge flying cars and avoid getting caught by the flying police cars. The game also has flying car races where the player races to the first place.\n\n==Reception==\n\n{{Video game reviews\n| GR = 59% <ref name=\"gamerankings\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerankings.com/pc/534359-beam-breakers/index.html |title=Beam Breakers for PC |publisher=[[GameRankings]] |accessdate=2014-02-26}}</ref>\n| MC = 61/100 <ref name=\"metacritic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/beam-breakers |title=Beam Breakers for PC Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=2014-02-26}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 5.6/10 <ref name=\"GameSpot\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/beam-breakers-review/1900-2895271/ |title=Beam Breakers Review |publisher=[[GameSpot]] |author=Davis, Ryan |date=2002-11-05 |accessdate=2014-02-26}}</ref>\n| GSpy = {{Rating|2|5}} <ref name=\"GameSpy\">{{cite web|url=http://pc.gamespy.com/pc/beam-breakers/569647p1.html  |title=GameSpy: BeamBreakers |publisher=[[GameSpy]] |author=Brooks, Mark |date=2002-11-23 |accessdate=2014-02-26}}</ref>\n| IGN = 8.0 <ref name=\"IGN\">{{Cite web|url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2002/11/19/beam-breakers-review |title=Beam Breakers Review |publisher=[[IGN]] |author=Sulic, Ivan |date=2002-11-19 |accessdate=2014-02-26}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Beam Breakers'' received mixed reviews, and currently holds a 61 rating on [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"metacritic\" /> The game received an 8.0/10 from [[IGN]], with a positive review saying: \"Beam Breakers does manage to create and admirably deliver an enormous, believable, and simply awesome sense of scale and liveliness.\"<ref name=\"IGN\" /> However, [[GameSpot]] gave Beam Breakers a 5.6/10, and said \"Beam Breakers starts off with a solid concept, but it doesn't quite deliver on it. Though the game does provide a few visceral thrills, it's hard to recommend it to anyone other than someone who is hungry enough for some futuristic racing to look past the game's mediocre production values.\"<ref name=\"GameSpot\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:2002 video games]]\n[[Category:Racing video games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Windows-only games]]\n[[Category:Cyberpunk video games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Germany]]\n[[Category:Futuristic_racing_games]]\n\n==External Links==\n\n* [[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt10817106/?ref_=nv_sr_1?ref_=nv_sr_1]] on IMDb\n* [[https://gamefaqs.gamespot.com/pc/534359-beam-breakers]] on Gamefaqs\n* [[https://www.mobygames.com/game/windows/beam-breakers]] on Mobygames\n", "text_old": "{{reimprove|date = September 2017}}\n{{infobox video game\n|title = Beam Breakers\n|developer = Similis\n|publisher = [[JoWooD Productions]]\n|released = 2002\n|platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]] \n}}\n\n\n\n'''''Beam Breakers''''' is a [[racing video game|racing game]] released in 2002. It was published by [[JoWooD Productions]] and developed by Similis. The game takes place in the year 2173. It features flying cars in the city of New York.\n\n==Gameplay==\nThe highways of [[New York City]] are teeming with illegal rush-hour grave-racers. Bad racers end up scraped off the side of skyscrapers while good ones build reputations that some would literally kill for. This is no pedestrian street race scene. It's a contest of minds where confidence, control and a taste for razor's-edge maneuvers separate the original gangsters of the skies from the wannabes and has-been.\n\nBeam Breakers has five cities in 57-mission campaigns. The player has to dodge flying cars and avoid getting caught by the flying police cars. The game also has flying car races where the player races to the first place.\n\n==Reception==\n\n{{Video game reviews\n| GR = 59% <ref name=\"gamerankings\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerankings.com/pc/534359-beam-breakers/index.html |title=Beam Breakers for PC |publisher=[[GameRankings]] |accessdate=2014-02-26}}</ref>\n| MC = 61/100 <ref name=\"metacritic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/beam-breakers |title=Beam Breakers for PC Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=2014-02-26}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 5.6/10 <ref name=\"GameSpot\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/beam-breakers-review/1900-2895271/ |title=Beam Breakers Review |publisher=[[GameSpot]] |author=Davis, Ryan |date=2002-11-05 |accessdate=2014-02-26}}</ref>\n| GSpy = {{Rating|2|5}} <ref name=\"GameSpy\">{{cite web|url=http://pc.gamespy.com/pc/beam-breakers/569647p1.html  |title=GameSpy: BeamBreakers |publisher=[[GameSpy]] |author=Brooks, Mark |date=2002-11-23 |accessdate=2014-02-26}}</ref>\n| IGN = 8.0 <ref name=\"IGN\">{{Cite web|url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2002/11/19/beam-breakers-review |title=Beam Breakers Review |publisher=[[IGN]] |author=Sulic, Ivan |date=2002-11-19 |accessdate=2014-02-26}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Beam Breakers'' received mixed reviews, and currently holds a 61 rating on [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"metacritic\" /> The game received an 8.0/10 from [[IGN]], with a positive review saying: \"Beam Breakers does manage to create and admirably deliver an enormous, believable, and simply awesome sense of scale and liveliness.\"<ref name=\"IGN\" /> However, [[GameSpot]] gave Beam Breakers a 5.6/10, and said \"Beam Breakers starts off with a solid concept, but it doesn't quite deliver on it. Though the game does provide a few visceral thrills, it's hard to recommend it to anyone other than someone who is hungry enough for some futuristic racing to look past the game's mediocre production values.\"<ref name=\"GameSpot\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:2002 video games]]\n[[Category:Racing video games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Windows-only games]]\n[[Category:Cyberpunk video games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Germany]]\n[[Category:Futuristic_racing_games]]\n\n==External Links==\n\n* [[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt10817106/?ref_=nv_sr_1?ref_=nv_sr_1]] on IMDb\n* [[https://gamefaqs.gamespot.com/pc/534359-beam-breakers]] on Gamefaqs\n* [[https://www.mobygames.com/game/windows/beam-breakers]] on Mobygames\n", "name_user": "Tiftoo72", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding video game cover", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beam_Breakers"}
{"title_page": "Ernst van Heerden", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2012}}\n{{Use South African English|date=September 2012}}\n{{MedalTop}}\n{{MedalSport | [[Art competitions at the Summer Olympics|Art competition]]}}\n{{MedalSilver | [[1948 Summer Olympics|1948 London]] | [[Art competitions at the 1948 Summer Olympics|Lyric works]]}}\n{{MedalBottom}}\n'''Ernst van Heerden''' (20 March 1916 &ndash; 30 September 1997) was a leading [[Afrikaans]] [[poet]].\n\nBorn in Pearston, Eastern Cape, [[South Africa]], he was an openly [[gay]] academic famous for his poems on sport. He [[Matriculation in South Africa|matriculated]] at [[Grey High School]], [[Port Elizabeth]].  In 1948 he received a silver medal in the [[Olympic Games]] International Poetry Competition for ''Ses gedigte''/''Six poems''. He held the degrees of [[Master of Arts|M.A.]] ([[University of Stellenbosch]]), D.Litt. et Phil.(Ghent), Hon.D.Litt. ([[Rhodes University]]), Hon D.Litt. ([[University of the Witwatersrand]]). He was an Emeritus Professor of [[Afrikaans]] and Nederlands at [[University of the Witwatersrand|Wits]]. He also lectured at the [[University of Stellenbosch]] from 1943 to 1959. His hobby was the collection of South African works of art. He was the recipient of numerous awards, including the Hofmeyr prize for poetry in 1975.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060518084007/http://www.databaseolympics.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=VANHEERN01 profile]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Van Heerden, Ernstvan}}\n[[Category:1916 births]]\n[[Category:1997 deaths]]\n[[Category:South African poets]]\n[[Category:Afrikaner people]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from South Africa]]\n[[Category:Gay writers]]\n[[Category:Stellenbosch University alumni]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists in art competitions]]\n[[Category:Hertzog Prize winners for poetry]]\n[[Category:20th-century poets]]\n[[Category:Male poets]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1948 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:20th-century South African male writers]]\n\n\n{{SouthAfrica-poet-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2012}}\n{{Use South African English|date=September 2012}}\n{{MedalTop}}\n{{MedalSport | [[Art competitions at the Summer Olympics|Art competition]]}}\n{{MedalSilver | [[1948 Summer Olympics|1948 London]] | [[Art competitions at the 1948 Summer Olympics|Lyric works]]}}\n{{MedalBottom}}\n'''Ernst van Heerden''' (20 March 1916 &ndash; 30 September 1997) was a leading [[Afrikaans]] [[poet]].\n\nBorn in Pearston, Eastern Cape, [[South Africa]], he was an openly [[gay]] academic famous for his poems on sport. He [[Matriculation in South Africa|matriculated]] at [[Grey High School]], [[Port Elizabeth]].  In 1948 he received a silver medal in the [[Olympic Games]] International Poetry Competition for ''Ses gedigte''/''Six poems''. He held the degrees of [[Master of Arts|M.A.]] ([[University of Stellenbosch]]), D.Litt. et Phil.(Ghent), Hon.D.Litt. ([[Rhodes University]]), Hon D.Litt. ([[University of the Witwatersrand]]). He was an Emeritus Professor of [[Afrikaans]] and Nederlands at [[University of the Witwatersrand|Wits]]. He also lectured at the [[University of Stellenbosch]] from 1943 to 1959. His hobby was the collection of South African works of art. He was the recipient of numerous awards, including the Hofmeyr prize for poetry in 1975.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060518084007/http://www.databaseolympics.com/players/playerpage.htm?ilkid=VANHEERN01 profile]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Van Heerden, Ernstvan}}\n[[Category:1916 births]]\n[[Category:1997 deaths]]\n[[Category:South African poets]]\n[[Category:Afrikaner people]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from South Africa]]\n[[Category:Gay writers]]\n[[Category:Stellenbosch University alumni]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists in art competitions]]\n[[Category:Hertzog Prize winners for poetry]]\n[[Category:20th-century poets]]\n[[Category:Male poets]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1948 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:20th-century male writers]]\n\n\n{{SouthAfrica-poet-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ernst_van_Heerden"}
{"title_page": "Cosmo Pieterse", "text_new": "'''Cosmo George Leipoldt Pieterse''' (born 1930 in [[Windhoek]], [[Namibia]]) is a [[South Africa]]n playwright, actor,<ref>[https://etd.ohiolink.edu/rws_etd/document/get/osu1291211511/inline Melanie J. House, \"Their Place on the South African Stage: The Peninsula Dramatic Society and the Trafalgar Players\" (dissertation)], Graduate Program in Theatre, The Ohio State University\n2010.</ref> poet, literary critic and anthologist.<ref>Donald E. Herdeck, ''African Authors: a companion to Black African writing'', 1973, p. 344.</ref>\n\n==Education and career==\nCosmo Pieterse went to the [[University of Cape Town]] and taught in [[Cape Town]] until leaving South Africa in 1965. He was banned under the [[Riotous Assemblies Act]] of 1962.<ref>[[Alex La Guma]], ''Apartheid: a collection of writings on South African racism by South Africans''. New York: International Publishers, 1971, p. 76.</ref> He subsequently taught in [[London]] and at [[Ohio University]] in the United States:<ref>Hans Karssenberg, [http://www.inspiringcities.org/index.php?id=18257&type=article City Poem 67- Cape Town] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007080823/http://www.inspiringcities.org/index.php?id=18257&type=article |date=2011-10-07 }}, 1 January 2004.</ref> arriving at Ohio University in 1970, he became a tenured faculty member in 1976. However, after travelling to meet his London publisher in 1979 he was denied re-entry to the US on classified information, allegedly for being \"a suspected communist\".<ref>[[John Shattuck]], \"Appendix A. Federal Restrictions on the Free Flow of Academic Information and Ideas\", in Association of Research Libraries, ''Minutes of the Meeting, Issues 107-109'', p. A.28.</ref><ref>[http://www.trinidadexpress.com/commentaries/In-tribute-to-Nelson-Mandela-236131011.html Selwyn Cudjoe, \"In tribute to Nelson Mandela\"], ''Trinidad Express Newspapers'', 16 December 2013.</ref>\n\nIn London Pieterse worked for the [[BBC World Service]] at [[Bush House]] in the later 1960s and early '70s.<ref>[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/debate/article-2172461/BBC-bids-goodbye-Bush-House-In-Memory-Beebs-iconic-Aldwych-home.html Lindsay Johns, \"In Memory of Bush House... on the day the home of the BBC World Service closes its doors for the last time\"], ''Mail Online'', 12 July 2012.</ref> Also an occasional actor, he appeared in ''The Burning'', a 1968 30-minute short drama film directed by [[Stephen Frears]].<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0290151/?ref_=nm_flmg_act_1 \"The Burning (1968)\"], IMDb.</ref><ref>[http://www.theepochtimes.com/n2/arts-entertainment/united-we-stand-south-african-cinema-during-apartheid-54172.html Joe Bendel, \"United We Stand: South African Cinema During Apartheid\"], 5 April 2011.</ref><ref>[http://www.citwf.com/film48413.htm \"Burning, The\"], Complete Index To World Film.</ref> As a poet, Pieterse has been characterised as producing work that is very \"European in its tone, metaphors, and delivery\", as Laura Linda Holland writes: \"Cosmo Pieterse's poems, like those of [[Dennis Brutus|Brutus]], are heavily inundated with Western influences, concerns, and motifs while retaining a definite African bias....Cosmo Pieterse uses his love of words to create poetry of hope and renewal.\"<ref>[http://digitalcommons.mcmaster.ca/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=6996&context=opendissertations Holland, Laura Linda, \"A Critical Survey of Contemporary South African Poetry: The Language of Conflict and Commitment\" (1987)], pp. 41-43. Open Access Dissertations and Theses. Paper 5964.</ref>\n\nPieterse edited several anthologies of plays and poetry for the [[African Writers Series]] published by [[Heinemann (publisher)|Heinemann]].\n\n==Works edited==\n* ''Ten One-act Plays''. London: Heinemann Educational Books, African Writers Series 34, 1968.\n* (with Donald Munro) ''Protest & Conflict in African Literature'', Heinemann Educational, 1969.\n* ''Seven South African Poets: Poems of Exile''. African Writers Series 64. London: Heinemann Educational, 1971.\n* ''Short African Plays''. London: Heinemann, African Writers Series 78, 1972.\n* ''Five African Plays''. London: Heinemann, African Writers Series 114, 1972.\n* (with Dennis Duerden) ''African Writers Talking: a collection of radio interviews'', Holmes & Meier, 1972.\n* (with Gwyneth Henderson) ''Nine African Plays for Radio''. London: Heinemann, African Writers Series 114, 1973.\n* ''Echo and Choruses: \"Ballad of the Cells\", and selected shorter poems'', 1974.\n* (with [[George Hallett (Cape Town)|George Hallett]]) ''Present Lives Future Becoming: South African Landscape in Words and Pictures''. Guildford: Hickory Press Ltd, 1974.\n* (with [[Angus Calder]] and [[Jack Mapanje]]) ''Summer Fires: New Poetry of Africa'' - an anthology of entries from the BBC Arts and Africa Poetry Award. Heinemann Educational Books, 1983.\n* (with Amelia House) ''Nelson Mandelamandla''. Three Continents Press, 1989.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://pzacad.pitzer.edu/NAM/sophia/writers/pieterse.shtml Sophiatown Renaissance (1952-60): Cosmo Pieterse]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pieterse, Cosmo}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:South African dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Ohio University faculty]]\n[[Category:South African poets]]\n[[Category:South African literary critics]]\n[[Category:University of Cape Town alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century South African male writers]]\n", "text_old": "'''Cosmo George Leipoldt Pieterse''' (born 1930 in [[Windhoek]], [[Namibia]]) is a [[South Africa]]n playwright, actor,<ref>[https://etd.ohiolink.edu/rws_etd/document/get/osu1291211511/inline Melanie J. House, \"Their Place on the South African Stage: The Peninsula Dramatic Society and the Trafalgar Players\" (dissertation)], Graduate Program in Theatre, The Ohio State University\n2010.</ref> poet, literary critic and anthologist.<ref>Donald E. Herdeck, ''African Authors: a companion to Black African writing'', 1973, p. 344.</ref>\n\n==Education and career==\nCosmo Pieterse went to the [[University of Cape Town]] and taught in [[Cape Town]] until leaving South Africa in 1965. He was banned under the [[Riotous Assemblies Act]] of 1962.<ref>[[Alex La Guma]], ''Apartheid: a collection of writings on South African racism by South Africans''. New York: International Publishers, 1971, p. 76.</ref> He subsequently taught in [[London]] and at [[Ohio University]] in the United States:<ref>Hans Karssenberg, [http://www.inspiringcities.org/index.php?id=18257&type=article City Poem 67- Cape Town] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007080823/http://www.inspiringcities.org/index.php?id=18257&type=article |date=2011-10-07 }}, 1 January 2004.</ref> arriving at Ohio University in 1970, he became a tenured faculty member in 1976. However, after travelling to meet his London publisher in 1979 he was denied re-entry to the US on classified information, allegedly for being \"a suspected communist\".<ref>[[John Shattuck]], \"Appendix A. Federal Restrictions on the Free Flow of Academic Information and Ideas\", in Association of Research Libraries, ''Minutes of the Meeting, Issues 107-109'', p. A.28.</ref><ref>[http://www.trinidadexpress.com/commentaries/In-tribute-to-Nelson-Mandela-236131011.html Selwyn Cudjoe, \"In tribute to Nelson Mandela\"], ''Trinidad Express Newspapers'', 16 December 2013.</ref>\n\nIn London Pieterse worked for the [[BBC World Service]] at [[Bush House]] in the later 1960s and early '70s.<ref>[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/debate/article-2172461/BBC-bids-goodbye-Bush-House-In-Memory-Beebs-iconic-Aldwych-home.html Lindsay Johns, \"In Memory of Bush House... on the day the home of the BBC World Service closes its doors for the last time\"], ''Mail Online'', 12 July 2012.</ref> Also an occasional actor, he appeared in ''The Burning'', a 1968 30-minute short drama film directed by [[Stephen Frears]].<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0290151/?ref_=nm_flmg_act_1 \"The Burning (1968)\"], IMDb.</ref><ref>[http://www.theepochtimes.com/n2/arts-entertainment/united-we-stand-south-african-cinema-during-apartheid-54172.html Joe Bendel, \"United We Stand: South African Cinema During Apartheid\"], 5 April 2011.</ref><ref>[http://www.citwf.com/film48413.htm \"Burning, The\"], Complete Index To World Film.</ref> As a poet, Pieterse has been characterised as producing work that is very \"European in its tone, metaphors, and delivery\", as Laura Linda Holland writes: \"Cosmo Pieterse's poems, like those of [[Dennis Brutus|Brutus]], are heavily inundated with Western influences, concerns, and motifs while retaining a definite African bias....Cosmo Pieterse uses his love of words to create poetry of hope and renewal.\"<ref>[http://digitalcommons.mcmaster.ca/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=6996&context=opendissertations Holland, Laura Linda, \"A Critical Survey of Contemporary South African Poetry: The Language of Conflict and Commitment\" (1987)], pp. 41-43. Open Access Dissertations and Theses. Paper 5964.</ref>\n\nPieterse edited several anthologies of plays and poetry for the [[African Writers Series]] published by [[Heinemann (publisher)|Heinemann]].\n\n==Works edited==\n* ''Ten One-act Plays''. London: Heinemann Educational Books, African Writers Series 34, 1968.\n* (with Donald Munro) ''Protest & Conflict in African Literature'', Heinemann Educational, 1969.\n* ''Seven South African Poets: Poems of Exile''. African Writers Series 64. London: Heinemann Educational, 1971.\n* ''Short African Plays''. London: Heinemann, African Writers Series 78, 1972.\n* ''Five African Plays''. London: Heinemann, African Writers Series 114, 1972.\n* (with Dennis Duerden) ''African Writers Talking: a collection of radio interviews'', Holmes & Meier, 1972.\n* (with Gwyneth Henderson) ''Nine African Plays for Radio''. London: Heinemann, African Writers Series 114, 1973.\n* ''Echo and Choruses: \"Ballad of the Cells\", and selected shorter poems'', 1974.\n* (with [[George Hallett (Cape Town)|George Hallett]]) ''Present Lives Future Becoming: South African Landscape in Words and Pictures''. Guildford: Hickory Press Ltd, 1974.\n* (with [[Angus Calder]] and [[Jack Mapanje]]) ''Summer Fires: New Poetry of Africa'' - an anthology of entries from the BBC Arts and Africa Poetry Award. Heinemann Educational Books, 1983.\n* (with Amelia House) ''Nelson Mandelamandla''. Three Continents Press, 1989.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://pzacad.pitzer.edu/NAM/sophia/writers/pieterse.shtml Sophiatown Renaissance (1952-60): Cosmo Pieterse]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pieterse, Cosmo}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:South African dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Ohio University faculty]]\n[[Category:South African poets]]\n[[Category:South African literary critics]]\n[[Category:University of Cape Town alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century male writers]]\n\n{{SouthAfrica-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:recat, removed stub tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cosmo_Pieterse"}
{"title_page": "Johannes Kerkorrel", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Johannes Kerkorrel\n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| landscape           = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Ralph John Rabie\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| alias               = \n| birth_date          = 27 March 1960\n| birth_place         = [[Johannesburg]], South Africa\n| origin              = \n| death_date          = {{death date and age|df=yes|2002|11|12|1960|03|27}}\n| death_place         = [[Kleinmond, Western Cape|Kleinmond]], near [[Cape Town]],<br/>South Africa\n| genre               = \n| occupation          = \n| instrument          = \n| years_active        = 1986\u20132002\n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n\n'''Johannes Kerkorrel''' (27 March 1960 \u2013 12 November 2002), born '''Ralph John Rabie''', was a South African singer-songwriter, journalist and playwright.<ref name=SAInfo>{{cite web|title='Dylan' of Afrikaans rock dies|url=http://www.southafrica.info/about/arts/johannes-kerkorrel.htm#.UXLtO6JTCz4|date=13 November 2002|publisher=SouthAfrica.info|accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref><ref name=Sassen>{{cite web |title=Just Another Day in Africa: In no-man's land I got lost |date=15 January 2003 |first=Robyn |last=Sassen |work=[[PopMatters.com]] |url=http://www.popmatters.com/columns/sassen/030115.shtml |accessdate=13 November 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nRabie, who was born in [[Johannesburg]], worked as a journalist for the [[Afrikaans]] newspapers ''[[Die Burger]]'' and ''[[Rapport (newspaper)|Rapport]]''.<ref>[[Jani Allan|Allan, Jani]]. [http://janiallan.com/2016/03/18/afrikaner-pride-passion-mixed-fun-laughter-new-era-boere-punks/ Afrikaner pride and passion mix with fun and laughter] ''Sunday Times'' (South Africa). 9 July 1989</ref> In 1986, Rabie started performing politically themed [[cabaret]] at [[arts festival]]s under his new stage name (''kerkorrel'' meaning [[church organ]] in Afrikaans). At that time, [[apartheid]] was at its [[nadir]] under [[State President of South Africa|State President]] [[P.W. Botha]]'s [[National Party (South Africa)|National Party]]-led government.\n\nIn 1987, Rabie was fired by ''Rapport'' for using quotes from Botha's speeches in his music; he then became a full-time musician and performer under the name ''Johannes Kerkorrel en die Gereformeerde Blues Band'' (Johannes Kerkorrel and the Reformed Blues Band), a deliberate reference to the [[Afrikaner Calvinism|Reformed Church]]. The band also included the Afrikaans singer-songwriter [[Koos Kombuis]]. Their brand of new Afrikaans music was dubbed ''alternatiewe Afrikaans'' (alternative Afrikaans) and exposed divergent political views to a new generation of [[Afrikaner]]s.<ref name=SAInfo/><ref name=Sassen/>\n\nIn 1985, they released the album ''[[Eet Kreef]]'' (''Eat Crayfish'') on the now-defunct [[Shifty Records]] label, which was a commercial success despite its tracks being banned from [[airplay (song)|radio airplay]] by the state-controlled [[South African Broadcasting Corporation]], which was the [[government mouthpiece]]. Colloquially, 'Eet Kreef' is ambiguous, meaning either 'Enjoy!' or 'Get lost!'.\n\nThe subsequent regional tour of college campuses and art festivals was called ''Vo\u00eblvry'' (literally ''free as a bird'' but here meaning ''outlawed''), and Rabie's controversial reinvention of [[Afrikaans]] [[popular music]] became known as the ''[[The Vo\u00eblvry Movement|Vo\u00eblvry movement]]''.<ref name=SAInfo/><ref name=Sassen/>\n\nIn 1990, Rabie visited [[Amsterdam]], and almost simultaneously the track ''[[Hillbrow]]'' from the ''Eet Kreef'' album became a hit in [[Belgium]], and Rabie followed its success with a solo tour. In subsequent years he enjoyed substantial artistic success in Belgium and the [[Netherlands]], and spent much of his time in [[Belgium]].  Here he also befriended [[Stef Bos]], a Dutch cabaret artist, with whom he would share a number of concerts.<ref name=SAInfo/><ref name=Sassen/>\n<!-- missing a lot of info post-apartheid -->\n\n==Death==\nRabie hanged himself on 12 November 2002 in [[Kleinmond]], near [[Hermanus]] on the [[Western Cape]] coast. He was survived by his long-term gay partner, and by his ex-wife and son.<ref>{{cite news|last=Redelinghuys|first=Pieter|title=Kerkorrel commits suicide|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/Kerkorrel-commits-suicide-20021112|accessdate=22 April 2013|newspaper=News24|date=12 November 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Remembering Kerkorrel|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2002-01-01-remembering-kerkorrel|accessdate=21 April 2013|newspaper=Mail & Guardian|date=13 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Rooi|first=Jacob|title='I'm sorry mom'|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/Im-sorry-mom-20021117|accessdate=21 April 2013|newspaper=Rapport|date=17 November 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title='Who killed Kerkorrel?'|url=http://www.news24.com/Entertainment/SouthAfrica/Who-killed-Kerkorrel-20050825|accessdate=20 April 2013|newspaper=News24|date=25 August 2005}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n*1995 [[South African Music Awards|SAMA]] \u2013 Best Pop Music Performance for ''[[Cyanide in the Beefcake]]''<ref name=SAInfo/>\n*1997 SAMA \u2013 Best Male Vocalist and Best Adult Contemporary Album: Afrikaans for ''[[Ge-trans-for-meer]]''<ref>{{cite news|title=The long road ahead|url=http://mg.co.za/article/1997-05-02-the-long-road-ahead|accessdate=21 April 2013|newspaper=Mail & Guardian|date=2 May 1997}}</ref>\n*2001 Geraas \u2013 Best pop album and Best adaptation for ''Die Ander Kant''<ref>{{cite news|last=Malan|first=Mariana|title=First Geraas award ceremony|url=http://www.news24.com/xArchive/Archive/First-Geraas-award-ceremony-20011106|accessdate=21 April 2013|newspaper=Die Burger Wes|date=6 November 2001}}</ref>\n*2013 SAMA \u2013 Lifetime Achievement Award<ref>{{cite news|title=Music veterans to be honoured at SA Music Awards|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2013-04-03-music-veterans-to-be-honoured-as-sa-music-awards|newspaper=Mail & Guardian|date=3 April 2013|accessdate=21 April 2013|quote=Kerkorrel was a prominent icon of the alternative Afrikaans music scene and a significant player in the vibrant 'Vo\u00eblvry' cultural movement. The Vo\u00eblvry movement was the 'Boere Beatlemania' of the late 1980s, whose main proponents sported undeniably kitsch names like Koos Kombuis and Johannes Kerkorrel. But far from being incidental, this eccentric bunch of young Afrikaans artists became the voice of their generation when South Africa was pushed to the brink of collapse by apartheid. Under the Vo\u00eblvry banner, their goal was the emancipation of Afrikaner youth from the strictures of their authoritarian, patriarchal culture \u2013 to make it cool to be Afrikaans. Kerkorrel's life has been celebrated in a wave of tributes following his untimely death at the age of 42 in 2002.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Leonard|first=Charles|title=Johannes Kerkorrel: The wise fool who left the fray|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2013-05-10-00-johannes-kerkorrel-the-wise-fool-who-left-the-fray|accessdate=13 May 2013|newspaper=Mail & Guardian|date=10 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n* ''[[Eet Kreef]]'' (1989)\n* ''[[Bloudruk]]'' (1992)\n* ''[[Cyanide in the Beefcake]]'' (1994) \n* ''[[Ge-trans-for-meer]]'' (1996) \n* ''Tien Jaar Later'' (1998)\n* ''Sing Koos du Plessis'' (1999)\n* ''Die Ander Kant'' (2000)\n* ''Vo\u00eblvry Die Toer'' (2002)\n* ''Kerkorrel \u2013 Best Of: P\u00earels Voor Die Swyne'' (2003)\n* ''Hoe Ek Voel'' (2012) \u2013 issued to commemorate the 10 year anniversary of Rabie's death<ref>{{cite web|title=Die 10-jaar herdenking van Johannes Kerkorrel se dood|url=http://www.ja.fm/blog/die-10-jaar-herdenking-van-johannes-kerkorrel-se-dood/|date=8 November 2012|publisher=ja.fm|accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Tributes==\nAfter Rabie's death, several artists recorded tribute songs to his life and work. An incomplete list follows:\n* [[Stef Bos]] \u2013 ''Pelgrimsrus''\n* [[Riku L\u00e4tti]] \u2013 ''Ysbeer''\n* [[Amanda Strydom]] \u2013 ''Ek Het Gedroom''\n* [[Karen Zoid]] \u2013 ''Foto Teen Die Muur''\n* [[Jak De Priester]] \u2013 ''Kerkorrel''\n* [[Kristoe Strauss]] \u2013 ''Sit Dit Self Af''\n* [[Jan Blohm]] \u2013 ''Johnny K''\n* [[Valiant Swart]] en [[Koos Kombuis]] \u2013 ''Kleinmond Koebaai''\n* [[Koos Kombuis]] - ''Johnny is nie dood nie''\n\n==Covers==\nRabie is a much covered artist. Among the cover versions that exist are: \n* [[Stef Bos]] \u2013 ''Hillbrow''\n* [[Riku L\u00e4tti]] \u2013 ''Somer''\n* [[Amanda Strydom]] \u2013 ''Hoe Ek Voel'' and ''Halala Afrika''\n* [[Van Coke Kartel]] - ''Energie''\n* [[:af:Refentse Morake]] - ''Halala Afrika''\n\n==Legacy==\nThe film ''Johnny is nie dood nie'' portrays a fictional group of friends meeting up after his suicide, looking back to the events leading up to the Vo\u00eblvry movement, and how his music inspired and influenced them.<ref name=\"week_Revi\">{{Cite web | title = Review: 'Johnny is nie dood nie' | last = SMITH | first = THERESA | work = WeekendSpecial | date = 4 May 2017 | accessdate = 2017-10-23 | url = https://weekendspecial.co.za/johnny-nie-dood-nie/ | quote =  }}</ref><ref name=\"chan_John\">{{Cite web | title = Johnny is nie dood nie | last = Zietsman | first = Gabi | work = Channel24 | date = 5 May 2017 | accessdate = 2017-10-23 | url = http://www.channel24.co.za/Movies/Reviews/johnny-is-nie-dood-nie-20170421 | language =   | quote =  }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Bernoldus Niemand]]\n* [[Koos Kombuis]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin|indent=yes}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Laubscher |first=Leswin |year=2005 |title=Afrikaner identity and the music of Johannes Kerkorrel |journal=South African Journal of Psychology |volume=35 |issue=2 |pages=308\u2013330 |publisher=Psychological Society of South Africa |doi= 10.1177/008124630503500209|url=https://www.academia.edu/388192/Afrikaner_identity_and_the_music_of_Johannes_Kerkorrel |accessdate=21 April 2013|quote=As old identity verities are dislodged, post-apartheid South Africa is witness to dramatic identitary flux. This study examines Afrikaner identity and particularly that of the generational cohort who witnessed the end of apartheid as young adults. Employing a hermeneutic semiology, the study provides a reading of Johannes Kerkorrel's music, arguing that, as cultural text, it enacts identitary discourse and tension. As such, several identitary moments and motifs are noted across a period of roughly 20 years, including that of identity as rebellion, location and individualising interiority. Finally, it is suggested that the law-of-the-father, as apartheid bequest, organises and animates identity struggles for this generation.}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Viljoen|first=Martina|title=Johannes Kerkorrel en postapartheid-Afrikaneridentiteit|date=1 November 2005|language=Afrikaans|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Johannes+Kerkorrel+en+postapartheid-Afrikaneridentiteit.-a0155039300|accessdate=21 April 2013|journal=Literator|issn=0258-2279|publisher=Literator Society of South Africa|trans-title=Johannes Kerkorrel and post Apartheid Afrikaaner Identity}}\n*{{cite book|last=Hopkins|first=Pat|title=Vo\u00eblvry the movement that rocked South Africa|year=2006|publisher=Zebra Press|location=Cape Town|isbn=9781770071209|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8lr1FloqLZsC}}\n*{{cite thesis |type=MA |first=Hendrick Michael Grobler |last=Uys |title=A psycho-biographical study of Ralph John Rabie |publisher=NMMU |year=2011|hdl=10948/1366}}\n*{{cite web|title=Johannes Kerkorrel|url=http://www.roekeloos.co.za/argief/kerkorrel.html|publisher=roekeloos.co.za|accessdate=21 April 2013|language=Afrikaans}} \n*{{cite web|title=Music Artists: Johannes Kerkorrel |url=http://entertainmentafrica.mobi/music/view/artist/308 |publisher=Entertainmentafrica Mobile |accessdate=21 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029213207/http://entertainmentafrica.mobi/music/view/artist/308 |archivedate=29 October 2013 }}\n*{{cite web|title=Vo\u00eblvry|url=http://www.shifty.co.za/shif4.html|publisher=Shifty|accessdate=22 April 2013|quote=Ralph Rabie, who was at that time a journalist on an Afrikaans paper, went down to Cape Town to interview Andr\u00e9 when V\u00ear van die ou Kalahari was released. There was a meeting of minds which eventually led to both of them playing in the first incarnation of the Gereformeerde Blues Band. A short while later, Andr\u00e9 left to forge a solo career as Koos Kombuis, while Ralph, by then known as Johannes Kerkorrel, went on to record the seminal Eet Kreef album with the remaining members of the GBB. Both artists featured on the Vo\u00eblvry compilation, which came out around this time.|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029204043/http://www.shifty.co.za/shif4.html|archivedate=29 October 2013|df=dmy-all}} \n*{{cite web|title=Johannes Kerkorrel & GBB|url=http://www.shifty.co.za/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=16&Itemid=37|publisher=Shifty|accessdate=22 April 2013|quote=Slashing their way out of the Nationalist Party ideology, the GBB charted the wide open spaces of a new Afrikaner rebellion. This time the insurrection was a musical one, with the GBB as rock & roll outlaws slinging guitars and stinging criticism against the laager mentality of volks kultuur and the apartheid way of life. Moving conventional rock into the realm of political theatre and satire as successfully as they did proved that if the GBB were to be seen as cultural upstarts, they were upstarts with a vision both innovative and lucid that could not be ignored.}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kerkorrel, Johannes}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century South African male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century South African singers]]\n[[Category:Afrikaans-language singers]]\n[[Category:Gay musicians]]\n[[Category:Gay writers]]\n[[Category:LGBT dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:LGBT musicians from South Africa]]\n[[Category:LGBT singers]]\n[[Category:LGBT songwriters]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from South Africa]]\n[[Category:Male dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Male suicides]]\n[[Category:Singers who committed suicide]]\n[[Category:South African dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:South African journalists]]\n[[Category:South African musicians]]\n[[Category:South African singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Suicides by hanging in South Africa]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Johannes Kerkorrel\n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| landscape           = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Ralph John Rabie\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| alias               = \n| birth_date          = 27 March 1960\n| birth_place         = [[Johannesburg]], South Africa\n| origin              = \n| death_date          = {{death date and age|df=yes|2002|11|12|1960|03|27}}\n| death_place         = [[Kleinmond, Western Cape|Kleinmond]], near [[Cape Town]],<br/>South Africa\n| genre               = \n| occupation          = \n| instrument          = \n| years_active        = 1986\u20132002\n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n\n'''Johannes Kerkorrel''' (27 March 1960 \u2013 12 November 2002), born '''Ralph John Rabie''', was a South African singer-songwriter, journalist and playwright.<ref name=SAInfo>{{cite web|title='Dylan' of Afrikaans rock dies|url=http://www.southafrica.info/about/arts/johannes-kerkorrel.htm#.UXLtO6JTCz4|date=13 November 2002|publisher=SouthAfrica.info|accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref><ref name=Sassen>{{cite web |title=Just Another Day in Africa: In no-man's land I got lost |date=15 January 2003 |first=Robyn |last=Sassen |work=[[PopMatters.com]] |url=http://www.popmatters.com/columns/sassen/030115.shtml |accessdate=13 November 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nRabie, who was born in [[Johannesburg]], worked as a journalist for the [[Afrikaans]] newspapers ''[[Die Burger]]'' and ''[[Rapport (newspaper)|Rapport]]''.<ref>[[Jani Allan|Allan, Jani]]. [http://janiallan.com/2016/03/18/afrikaner-pride-passion-mixed-fun-laughter-new-era-boere-punks/ Afrikaner pride and passion mix with fun and laughter] ''Sunday Times'' (South Africa). 9 July 1989</ref> In 1986, Rabie started performing politically themed [[cabaret]] at [[arts festival]]s under his new stage name (''kerkorrel'' meaning [[church organ]] in Afrikaans). At that time, [[apartheid]] was at its [[nadir]] under [[State President of South Africa|State President]] [[P.W. Botha]]'s [[National Party (South Africa)|National Party]]-led government.\n\nIn 1987, Rabie was fired by ''Rapport'' for using quotes from Botha's speeches in his music; he then became a full-time musician and performer under the name ''Johannes Kerkorrel en die Gereformeerde Blues Band'' (Johannes Kerkorrel and the Reformed Blues Band), a deliberate reference to the [[Afrikaner Calvinism|Reformed Church]]. The band also included the Afrikaans singer-songwriter [[Koos Kombuis]]. Their brand of new Afrikaans music was dubbed ''alternatiewe Afrikaans'' (alternative Afrikaans) and exposed divergent political views to a new generation of [[Afrikaner]]s.<ref name=SAInfo/><ref name=Sassen/>\n\nIn 1985, they released the album ''[[Eet Kreef]]'' (''Eat Crayfish'') on the now-defunct [[Shifty Records]] label, which was a commercial success despite its tracks being banned from [[airplay (song)|radio airplay]] by the state-controlled [[South African Broadcasting Corporation]], which was the [[government mouthpiece]]. Colloquially, 'Eet Kreef' is ambiguous, meaning either 'Enjoy!' or 'Get lost!'.\n\nThe subsequent regional tour of college campuses and art festivals was called ''Vo\u00eblvry'' (literally ''free as a bird'' but here meaning ''outlawed''), and Rabie's controversial reinvention of [[Afrikaans]] [[popular music]] became known as the ''[[The Vo\u00eblvry Movement|Vo\u00eblvry movement]]''.<ref name=SAInfo/><ref name=Sassen/>\n\nIn 1990, Rabie visited [[Amsterdam]], and almost simultaneously the track ''[[Hillbrow]]'' from the ''Eet Kreef'' album became a hit in [[Belgium]], and Rabie followed its success with a solo tour. In subsequent years he enjoyed substantial artistic success in Belgium and the [[Netherlands]], and spent much of his time in [[Belgium]].  Here he also befriended [[Stef Bos]], a Dutch cabaret artist, with whom he would share a number of concerts.<ref name=SAInfo/><ref name=Sassen/>\n<!-- missing a lot of info post-apartheid -->\n\n==Death==\nRabie hanged himself on 12 November 2002 in [[Kleinmond]], near [[Hermanus]] on the [[Western Cape]] coast. He was survived by his long-term gay partner, and by his ex-wife and son.<ref>{{cite news|last=Redelinghuys|first=Pieter|title=Kerkorrel commits suicide|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/Kerkorrel-commits-suicide-20021112|accessdate=22 April 2013|newspaper=News24|date=12 November 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Remembering Kerkorrel|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2002-01-01-remembering-kerkorrel|accessdate=21 April 2013|newspaper=Mail & Guardian|date=13 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Rooi|first=Jacob|title='I'm sorry mom'|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/Im-sorry-mom-20021117|accessdate=21 April 2013|newspaper=Rapport|date=17 November 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title='Who killed Kerkorrel?'|url=http://www.news24.com/Entertainment/SouthAfrica/Who-killed-Kerkorrel-20050825|accessdate=20 April 2013|newspaper=News24|date=25 August 2005}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n*1995 [[South African Music Awards|SAMA]] \u2013 Best Pop Music Performance for ''[[Cyanide in the Beefcake]]''<ref name=SAInfo/>\n*1997 SAMA \u2013 Best Male Vocalist and Best Adult Contemporary Album: Afrikaans for ''[[Ge-trans-for-meer]]''<ref>{{cite news|title=The long road ahead|url=http://mg.co.za/article/1997-05-02-the-long-road-ahead|accessdate=21 April 2013|newspaper=Mail & Guardian|date=2 May 1997}}</ref>\n*2001 Geraas \u2013 Best pop album and Best adaptation for ''Die Ander Kant''<ref>{{cite news|last=Malan|first=Mariana|title=First Geraas award ceremony|url=http://www.news24.com/xArchive/Archive/First-Geraas-award-ceremony-20011106|accessdate=21 April 2013|newspaper=Die Burger Wes|date=6 November 2001}}</ref>\n*2013 SAMA \u2013 Lifetime Achievement Award<ref>{{cite news|title=Music veterans to be honoured at SA Music Awards|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2013-04-03-music-veterans-to-be-honoured-as-sa-music-awards|newspaper=Mail & Guardian|date=3 April 2013|accessdate=21 April 2013|quote=Kerkorrel was a prominent icon of the alternative Afrikaans music scene and a significant player in the vibrant 'Vo\u00eblvry' cultural movement. The Vo\u00eblvry movement was the 'Boere Beatlemania' of the late 1980s, whose main proponents sported undeniably kitsch names like Koos Kombuis and Johannes Kerkorrel. But far from being incidental, this eccentric bunch of young Afrikaans artists became the voice of their generation when South Africa was pushed to the brink of collapse by apartheid. Under the Vo\u00eblvry banner, their goal was the emancipation of Afrikaner youth from the strictures of their authoritarian, patriarchal culture \u2013 to make it cool to be Afrikaans. Kerkorrel's life has been celebrated in a wave of tributes following his untimely death at the age of 42 in 2002.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Leonard|first=Charles|title=Johannes Kerkorrel: The wise fool who left the fray|url=http://mg.co.za/article/2013-05-10-00-johannes-kerkorrel-the-wise-fool-who-left-the-fray|accessdate=13 May 2013|newspaper=Mail & Guardian|date=10 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n* ''[[Eet Kreef]]'' (1989)\n* ''[[Bloudruk]]'' (1992)\n* ''[[Cyanide in the Beefcake]]'' (1994) \n* ''[[Ge-trans-for-meer]]'' (1996) \n* ''Tien Jaar Later'' (1998)\n* ''Sing Koos du Plessis'' (1999)\n* ''Die Ander Kant'' (2000)\n* ''Vo\u00eblvry Die Toer'' (2002)\n* ''Kerkorrel \u2013 Best Of: P\u00earels Voor Die Swyne'' (2003)\n* ''Hoe Ek Voel'' (2012) \u2013 issued to commemorate the 10 year anniversary of Rabie's death<ref>{{cite web|title=Die 10-jaar herdenking van Johannes Kerkorrel se dood|url=http://www.ja.fm/blog/die-10-jaar-herdenking-van-johannes-kerkorrel-se-dood/|date=8 November 2012|publisher=ja.fm|accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Tributes==\nAfter Rabie's death, several artists recorded tribute songs to his life and work. An incomplete list follows:\n* [[Stef Bos]] \u2013 ''Pelgrimsrus''\n* [[Riku L\u00e4tti]] \u2013 ''Ysbeer''\n* [[Amanda Strydom]] \u2013 ''Ek Het Gedroom''\n* [[Karen Zoid]] \u2013 ''Foto Teen Die Muur''\n* [[Jak De Priester]] \u2013 ''Kerkorrel''\n* [[Kristoe Strauss]] \u2013 ''Sit Dit Self Af''\n* [[Jan Blohm]] \u2013 ''Johnny K''\n* [[Valiant Swart]] en [[Koos Kombuis]] \u2013 ''Kleinmond Koebaai''\n* [[Koos Kombuis]] - ''Johnny is nie dood nie''\n\n==Covers==\nRabie is a much covered artist. Among the cover versions that exist are: \n* [[Stef Bos]] \u2013 ''Hillbrow''\n* [[Riku L\u00e4tti]] \u2013 ''Somer''\n* [[Amanda Strydom]] \u2013 ''Hoe Ek Voel'' and ''Halala Afrika''\n* [[Van Coke Kartel]] - ''Energie''\n* [[:af:Refentse Morake]] - ''Halala Afrika''\n\n==Legacy==\nThe film ''Johnny is nie dood nie'' portrays a fictional group of friends meeting up after his suicide, looking back to the events leading up to the Vo\u00eblvry movement, and how his music inspired and influenced them.<ref name=\"week_Revi\">{{Cite web | title = Review: 'Johnny is nie dood nie' | last = SMITH | first = THERESA | work = WeekendSpecial | date = 4 May 2017 | accessdate = 2017-10-23 | url = https://weekendspecial.co.za/johnny-nie-dood-nie/ | quote =  }}</ref><ref name=\"chan_John\">{{Cite web | title = Johnny is nie dood nie | last = Zietsman | first = Gabi | work = Channel24 | date = 5 May 2017 | accessdate = 2017-10-23 | url = http://www.channel24.co.za/Movies/Reviews/johnny-is-nie-dood-nie-20170421 | language =   | quote =  }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Bernoldus Niemand]]\n* [[Koos Kombuis]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin|indent=yes}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Laubscher |first=Leswin |year=2005 |title=Afrikaner identity and the music of Johannes Kerkorrel |journal=South African Journal of Psychology |volume=35 |issue=2 |pages=308\u2013330 |publisher=Psychological Society of South Africa |doi= 10.1177/008124630503500209|url=https://www.academia.edu/388192/Afrikaner_identity_and_the_music_of_Johannes_Kerkorrel |accessdate=21 April 2013|quote=As old identity verities are dislodged, post-apartheid South Africa is witness to dramatic identitary flux. This study examines Afrikaner identity and particularly that of the generational cohort who witnessed the end of apartheid as young adults. Employing a hermeneutic semiology, the study provides a reading of Johannes Kerkorrel's music, arguing that, as cultural text, it enacts identitary discourse and tension. As such, several identitary moments and motifs are noted across a period of roughly 20 years, including that of identity as rebellion, location and individualising interiority. Finally, it is suggested that the law-of-the-father, as apartheid bequest, organises and animates identity struggles for this 